Great question. You're right to question it — bbox pixel area is a weak proxy for "clearly visible". A large drone far away can have a small bbox, and a nano drone very close can have a large bbox. Area alone doesn't tell you if the drone is actually recognizable.
Better ideas for "clearly visible" gate
Here are the real options, ranked by how well they actually measure visibility:
1. Confidence score from Stage 1 (best simple option)
YOLO's own confidence score already encodes how "clear" the detection is. If conf < 0.6, the drone is probably blurry, partially occluded, or too small to distinguish. This is better than area because YOLO computes it from the actual image features, not just pixel count.
pythonif yolo_conf < 0.60:
    label = "drone (size N/A)"   # not confident enough
else:
    → Stage 2
2. Crop sharpness — Laplacian variance (best quality check)
After cropping the drone bbox, measure how sharp/blurry that crop actually is. A blurry crop will give Stage 2 garbage input regardless of bbox size. Laplacian variance is a standard, fast blur detector.
pythonimport cv2
def is_sharp(crop, threshold=80):
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(crop, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    return cv2.Laplacian(gray, cv2.CV_64F).var() > threshold

High variance = sharp, clear drone → classify
Low variance = blurry, out of focus → "size N/A"

3. Combine all three (recommended)
python# Gate conditions — ALL must pass to attempt classification
